Since the FTDI converter had not yet been obtained, the project development was 
continued using the computer's built-in camera. First, real-time video streaming
was established by accessing the camera with Python and the OpenCV library.
After successfully obtaining the camera feed, the design of the virtual piano 
interface was initiated. Using OpenCV's drawing functions, piano keys of specific
dimensions were displayed on the screen, and each key was assigned to its
corresponding musical note.

Next, the MediaPipe Hands library was integrated into the project to enable hand
detection. The required libraries were installed, allowing the hand and its 
landmarks to be detected in real time. The coordinates of the 21 hand landmarks 
identified by the model were examined and evaluated for use within the application.

In the final stage, the audio files corresponding to the piano notes were loaded
into the program. To simplify the initial implementation, only the tip of the 
thumb was used as the control point. When the thumb entered the area of a virtual 
piano key, the corresponding note was played. As a result, the first prototype of 
the virtual piano, operating with the computer's built-in camera, was successfully 
developed.
